# Fullstack Development: From Concept to Deployment

## Introduction

A fullstack developer is a specialist who can work with both frontend and backend parts of an application, as well as understand deployment processes and DevOps.

## Fullstack Application Architecture

```javascript
// Project structure
project/
├── frontend/          # React/Vue/Angular application
│   ├── src/
│   ├── public/
│   └── package.json
├── backend/           # Node.js/Python/Java server
│   ├── src/
│   ├── routes/
│   └── package.json
├── database/          # Schemas and migrations
├── docker/           # Docker configuration
└── docs/             # Documentation
```

## Frontend (React + TypeScript)

```typescript
// Component with TypeScript
interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

interface UserListProps {
  users: User[];
  onUserSelect: (user: User) => void;
}

const UserList: React.FC<UserListProps> = ({ users, onUserSelect }) => {
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

  const handleUserClick = async (user: User) => {
    try {
      setLoading(true);
      await onUserSelect(user);
    } catch (err) {
      setError(err.message);
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div className="user-list">
      {users.map(user => (
        <div key={user.id} onClick={() => handleUserClick(user)}>
          <h3>{user.name}</h3>
          <p>{user.email}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};
```

## Backend (Node.js + Express)

```javascript
// API server with Express
const express = require('express');
const cors = require('cors');
const helmet = require('helmet');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const app = express();

// Middleware
app.use(helmet());
app.use(cors({
  origin: process.env.FRONTEND_URL,
  credentials: true
}));

// Rate limiting
const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100 // maximum 100 requests
});
app.use('/api/', limiter);

// Routes
app.use('/api/users', require('./routes/users'));
app.use('/api/auth', require('./routes/auth'));
app.use('/api/products', require('./routes/products'));

// Error handling
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack);
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
});

module.exports = app;
```

